>>44385725
I have no idea what stories you're referencing. That is the first time I've heard anything claiming there can be only one kitsune with nine tails at a time, and I've spent a lot of time looking up and reading folk tales about yokai.

The pranks aren't a universal theme at all. Being crafty yes, but calling it pranks is missing out on the perception of foxes people had. There were mischievous to downright malicious kitsune, there were kitsune acting as divine messengers, there were kitsune that were basically local kami, kitsune that were evil spirits, etc. The perception of them changed as culture changed, and culture doesn't change everywhere at the same speed or with the same needs. Also, throughout various points in history if someone was particularly weird they were often said to have the blood of a kitsune in them.

Of the few things that're probably universal about kitsune in particular is that they do not like dogs and vice versa, they can pretend to be/shapeshift into/possess (depends on time period & region) humans, and the more tails they have the older and more powerful they are.

Fox spirits are all over asia, yes. The common root to the multiple tails comes from the old chinese idea that the longer an animal lives the more magical and powerful it becomes. A common telling from china is that foxes had their tails split every 50 or 100 years and once they hit a certain number of tails they were powerful enough to present as human.
